  "original_title": "\u0db8\u0dd2\u0dbd \u0db4\u0dcf\u0dbd\u0db1\u0dba \u0d9a\u0dd2\u0dbb\u0dd3\u0db8\u0dd9\u0db1\u0dca \u0db7\u0dcf\u0dab\u0dca\u0da9 \u0dc3\u0db3\u0dc4\u0dcf \u0d9a\u0dd8\u0dad\u0dd2\u0db8 \u0dc4\u0dd2\u0d9f\u0dba\u0d9a\u0dca \u0d87\u0dad\u0dd2\u0dc0\u0dda",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Price controls create artificial scarcity of goods",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "Mr. Iran Wickramaratne, Member of Parliament of Samagi Jana Balavega, says that in this era of market economy of the country, if the price of goods is determined according to the demand and supply, the price control and the issuing of gazettes will lead to an artificial shortage of goods.",
        "Sri Lanka has now been included among the 5 countries with the highest food inflation. We are below Ethiopia. Consumers cannot even think about consuming meat and fish. Now the price of eggs has skyrocketed. The government has issued a gazette under the Consumer Authority Act setting a control price for eggs. She emphasized that the government should understand that since the country has a market economy today, controlling prices through the gazette is an outdated method.",
        "A price control has been set by reducing the price of an egg sold at Rs 65 in the market to Rs 45. Similarly, to control the price of rice, the government issued 13 gazettes within the last two years specifying various figures. The government had to reverse all those gazettes due to the inability to control the price of rice through those gazettes. The same fate has already happened to the gazette issued to control the price of eggs."
      ],
